'%{
\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cChildren are coached on how to jump through a thousand scholastic hoops. Yet by far the most important decisions they will make are about whom to marry and whom to befriend, what to love and what to despise, and how to control impulses. On these matters, they are almost\n\nJune 13, 2017\n\u001c11\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\nChapter 1 - Decision Making\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cMembers of the Composure Class spend much of their adult lives going into rooms and making everybody else feel inferior. This effect is only magnified by the fact that they are sincere, modest, and nice. Nothing gives them greater pleasure than inviting you out to their weekend place. This involves meeting them Friday afternoon at some private airport. They arrive with their belongings in a tote bag because when you have your own plane you don’t need luggage that actually closes.\n\nOctober 16, 2015\n\u001c17\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cRob registered her overall level of attractiveness, subliminally aware that attractive people generally earn significantly higher incomes.\n\nOctober 16, 2015\n\u001c19\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cJanine Willis and Alexander Todorov of Princeton have found that people can make snap judgments about a person’s trustworthiness, competence, aggressiveness and likability within the first tenth of a second. These sorts of first glimpses are astonishingly accurate in predicting how people will feel about each other months later. People rarely revise their first impression, they just become more confident that they are right. I\n\nOctober 16, 2015\n\u001c22\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cHe was tall, and since one study estimated that each inch of height corresponds to $6,000 of annual salary in contemporary America, that matters.\n\nOctober 16, 2015\n\u001c23\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cAs Helen Fisher wrote in a chapter of The New Psychology of Love , “Most men and women fall in love with individuals of the same ethnic, social, religious, educational and economic background, those of similar physical attractiveness, a comparable intelligence, similar attitudes, expectations, values, interests, and those with similar social and communication skills.”\n\nOctober 16, 2015\n\u001c24\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cReason is nestled upon emotion and dependent upon it. Emotion assigns value to things, and reason can only make choices on the basis of those valuations.\n\nOctober 16, 2015\n\u001c36\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cFinally, we are primarily wanderers, not decision makers. Over the past century, people have tended to conceive decision making as a point in time. You amass the facts and circumstances and evidence and then make a call. In fact, it is more accurate to say that we are pilgrims in a social landscape. We wander across an\n\nOctober 16, 2015\n\u001c37\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\nChapter 3 - Mindsight\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cOctober 16, 2015\n\u001c48\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cOctober 16, 2015\n\u001c50\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\nChapter 5 - Attachment\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cprisoner of his impulses.\n\nOctober 18, 2015\n\u001c77\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cFreedom without structure is its own slavery.\n\nOctober 18, 2015\n\u001c77\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cAs she did this, his eyes were rapt upon her. She was treating him with respect and letting him into that most mysterious region—the hidden zone of his mother’s life that had existed before his birth. His time horizon subtly widened. He got subtle intimations of his mother’s girlhood, her maturity, his arrival, his growth, this moment now, and the adventures he would someday have\n\nOctober 18, 2015\n\u001c79\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cIf there is one thing developmental psychologists have learned over the years, it is that parents don’t have to be brilliant psychologists to succeed. They don’t have to be supremely gifted teachers. Most of the stuff parents do with flashcards and special drills and tutorials to hone their kids into perfect achievement machines don’t have any effect at all. Instead, parents just have to be good enough. They have to provide their kids with stable and predictable rhythms. They need to be able to fall in tune with their kids’ needs,\n\nOctober 18, 2015\n\u001c80\n\u0011\n\u0011"},{"ty":"ae","et":"inline","id":"i.0","epm":{"ee_eo":{"eo_bo":{"ln_c":"#000000","ln_s":0,"ln_w":0.0},"eo_lco":{"lc_oi":"","lc_cs":"","lc_ct":0,"lc_sci":""},"i_wth":105.0,"eo_rd":null,"eo_mb":1.5,"eo_at":null,"eo_hb":false,"eo_lc":null,"eo_rtd":"","i_crop":{"crop_oxr":0.0,"crop_oyr":0.0,"crop_rot":0.0,"crop_hr":1.0,"crop_wr":1.0},"i_ht":150.9375,"i_rot":0.0,"i_clst":{"cv":{"op":"set","opValue":[]}},"eo_ml":1.5,"i_bri":0.0,"eo_mr":1.5,"i_src":null,"eo_ad":"Cover Image","i_cid":"1THLmQdst2NlsvW4BC3gV2_h_wokpXAuEUUsybuM","i_cont":0.0,"i_opa":1.0,"eo_mt":1.5,"eo_type":0}}},{"ty":"ae","et":"inline","id":"i.1","epm":{"ee_eo":{"eo_bo":{"ln_c":"#000000","ln_s":0,"ln_w":0.0},"eo_lco":{"lc_oi":"","lc_cs":"","lc_ct":0,"lc_sci":""},"i_wth":24.0,"eo_rd":null,"eo_mb":1.5,"eo_at":null,"eo_hb":false,"eo_lc":null,"eo_rtd":"","i_crop":{"crop_oxr":0.0,"crop_oyr":0.0,"crop_rot":0.0,"crop_hr":1.0,"crop_wr":1.0},"i_ht":18.0,"i_rot":0.0,"i_clst":{"cv":{"op":"set","opValue":[]}},"eo_ml":1.5,"i_bri":0.0,"eo_mr":1.5,"i_src":null,"eo_ad":null,"i_cid":"1TNY0UCM2PcJfr2k0XKOUpS6cIrAt7urPqiMiwNc","i_cont":0.0,"i_opa":1.0,"eo_mt":1.5,"eo_type":0}}},{"ty":"ae","et":"inline","id":"i.10","epm":{"ee_eo":{"eo_bo":{"ln_c":"#000000","ln_s":0,"ln_w":0.0},"eo_lco":{"lc_oi":"","lc_cs":"",